@node give "Distribution"

Well, if you like Massive, then give Massive to any person you like.

If you don't like Massive, then give Massive to any person you don't like.

In other words:
It's FREEWARE!

 @{" Credits " link source}

@endnode


@node intro "Reminiscing..."

Maybe you remember "DrawMap" or "PlotMap", two Amiga programs that
could generate maps of any part of the world.  Massive has the same
purpose as these old-timers, but it's better:

 @{" Features " link feat}
 @{" Credits  " link source}

@endnode



@node Name1 "The name of the game"
@next feat

Massive stands for "MAp SyStem interactIVE"

Do you believe that?

 @{" Yes " link Haha}  @{"  No  " link Name2}

@endnode

@node Name2 "The name of the game"
@next feat

How about this explanation:

Massive got it's name because there is nothing more massive than our
Mother Earth -- and it was a massive work to get this toy done.

Do you believe that?

 @{" Yes " link Haha}  @{"  No  " link Name3}

@endnode

@node Name3 "The name of the game"
@next feat

I listened a lot to Massive Attack's album "Blue Lines" while I wrote
this cute program.

Do you believe that?

 @{" Yes " link Bingo}  @{"  No  " link Idiot}

@endnode

@node Bingo "Philosophy"
@next feat

Well, truth is a difficult thing -- mono-causal explanations usually do not
work in our complex world:  Just have a look at a Massive map and you will
understand that.

If that does not help:  Read some Plato and Hegel.

 @{" Contents " link main}
 @{" Credits  " link source}

@endnode

@node Idiot "The name of the game"
@next feat

Have you ever been told that you are a very mistrustful person?

 @{" Contents " link main}
 @{" Credits  " link source}

@endnode

@node haha "The name of the game"
@next feat

To be honest:  It seems to be fairly easy to fool you!

 @{" Contents " link main}
 @{" Credits  " link source}

@endnode



@node feat "List of Massive's unique and not so unique features"

Massive is a real cutie:

 -- It knows all 1998's international borders (unique for the AMIGA!)

 -- It can flood fill land masses automagically (unique for the AMIGA!)

 -- Zoom in on the Maldives and you'll know what precision is

 -- No problem to have the 180° meridian in the middle of a map

 -- Works with every possible screen mode from 320x200 to 1280x1024

 -- Reasonably fast

 -- @{" Non-Features " link non}

 @{" Credits " link source}

@endnode

@node non "What Massive cannot do"

Massive can not

 -- display rivers, cities and mountains

 -- make your breakfast

 @{" Plans for the future" link plans}
 @{" Credits             " link source}


@endnode


@node plans "What Massive will do tomorrow or the day after"

Future versions of Massive will display rivers, cities, mountains,
and they will be able to make breakfast for you.

And I might even write something like a documentation.

 @{" Contents " link main}
 @{" Credits  " link source}

@endnode



